data.title: MAURICE GRAN, co-writer of The New Statesman on Rik Mayall's dream role
data.meta_description: Rik Mayall told the show's writers: 'I want to play a character who is just like me. Vain, greedy, depraved, obsessed with money, and not afraid to kill.'
data.text:
I knew he'd would be a perfect B'Stard... MAURICE GRAN, co-writer of The New Statesman on how he created 'mesmerising' Rik Mayall's dream role

I first met Rik in 1986 at a comedy seminar in Cheltenham with my co-writer Laurence Marks. It was the height of his fame in the student sitcom The Young Ones and he said he was very keen to work with us.

He told us he wanted to do something a bit more grown-up, as the world saw him as a spotty, skinny youth: the radical student in a black blazer studded with political badges.

What most people hadn’t realised at the time was that Rik was surprisingly tall and extremely handsome, and he had these incredible eyes — they were mesmerising.

Scroll down for video

Despite his obvious talents, Laurence and I had already worked with a member of The Young Ones cast, Nigel Planer, who played Neil the hippie, and we had found the process too demanding. We suspected Rik might be the same. So we didn’t follow it up. Then, in one of those coincidences that makes me almost believe in a higher power, we found we were both guests with him on the Wogan chat show one night. Rik came up to us in the green room, and he said right away: ‘Why didn’t you phone me, you b******s?’

We asked him what he wanted to do, what was his dream role, and he was very honest. ‘I want to play a character who is just like me,’ he said. ‘Vain, greedy, depraved, obsessed with money, and not afraid to kill.’

It sounded to us like he wanted to play a Conservative backbencher. And so, The New Statesman, satirising the Tory government, was born. Rik as the scheming, lecherous Alan Beresford B’Stard was truly brilliant.

Truly brilliant: The New Statesman satirised the Tory government, with Mayall as the scheming, lecherous Alan Beresford B'Stard

Return: When Mayall reprised B'Stard for a stage play in 2006 his quad-bike crash had affected his ability to learn his lines, but he triumphed in the role

He was demanding to work with, but he also demanded a great deal of himself.

Rik had a guilty secret: he came from a lovely family, and as a result, he was beautifully well brought up with impeccable manners. At the end of each week’s recording, he would individually thank every member of the cast.

Rik was affected by his quad-bike crash in 1998. When we worked with him on the Alan B’Stard stage play in 2006, we realised the injury had affected his ability to learn lines — and it clearly frustrated him.

I told him it didn’t matter. ‘To be a brilliant comedian,’ I said, ‘you have to be funny, sexy, dangerous, the audience must love you, and you have to learn your lines. You’ve got four out of five of those things — and the lines I can write up on the wall!’

Regardless of his difficulties, Rik once again triumphed in the role of Alan, and dominated the stage for 90 out of the play’s 100 minutes.
